    2: {
      level: 2,
      summary: 'Preconception care involves optimizing medical conditions, updating vaccinations, reviewing medications, and adopting healthy behaviors before pregnancy to reduce risks for mother and fetus.',
      explanation: `**Core Components:**

*Folic Acid Supplementation:*
- All women: 400-800 mcg daily
- High-risk (prior NTD, obesity, diabetes, seizure medications): 4 mg daily
- Begin at least 1 month before conception, continue through first trimester

*Chronic Disease Optimization:*
- Diabetes: Target A1c <6.5% before conception (reduces birth defects)
- Hypertension: Review medications, switch if needed
- Thyroid: Optimize TSH, adjust medications
- Epilepsy: Review anticonvulsants for teratogenicity

*Medication Review:*
- Identify teratogenic medications
- Switch to safer alternatives
- Common concerns: ACE inhibitors, statins, some anticonvulsants, isotretinoin

*Vaccination Update:*
- MMR and varicella: Must be given before pregnancy (live vaccines)
- Hepatitis B: Complete series if not immune
- Tdap: Recommended during each pregnancy

*Infectious Disease Screening:*
- HIV, hepatitis B and C
- STIs (chlamydia, gonorrhea, syphilis)
- Rubella and varicella immunity

*Lifestyle Counseling:*
- Smoking cessation
- Alcohol avoidance
- Weight management (BMI 18.5-24.9 ideal)
- Diet and exercise

*Genetic Counseling:*
- Family history review
- Carrier screening (CF, SMA, hemoglobinopathies)
- Advanced maternal age considerations`,
